<h3 id="hdr-skunklabs-labs">Skunk Labs Labs</h3>

<p class="lead">
	Lab Workflow
</p>

<p>
	The lab workflow for Skunk Labs is pretty simple. There are five stages a lab can be in: proposed, started, completed, blocked and
	abandoned. Most of these are pretty self explanatory. All new lab ideas start out as <em>proposed</em> labs. The person whom proposed
	the lab idea is the <em>founder</em> of the lab. The founder then started defining the team roles they think would be required to
	successfully complete the lab. Only the founder can progress the lab into other stages.</p>
<p>
	The purpose of the other stages is pretty self explanatory. A <em>started</em> lab is a lab in progress. A <em>completed</em> lab
	is a lab that finished and the team feels that it has accomplished its goals. A <em>blocked</em> lab is one that the founder feels can
	be completed but progress is blocked for some reason such as requiring funding, organizational boundaries, etc. Finally, an <em>abandoned</em>
	lab is one that the founder feels cannot realistically be completed successfully.
</p>

<p class="lead">
	Lab Team
</p>

<p>
	Once the team is defined control largely spreads to the entire team. The founder has to select roles such as 'web developer' or 'programmer'
	and roles of that nature. Anyone can <em>take</em> any role they want. Once they click on <em>Take Role</em> they are a part of the lab's
	team and have full access to make changes to the lab. While only the founder can change the state (started, blocked, etc) the team at large
	edit the team roles, lab goals, and so on. This is because despite the fact this started as potentially one person's idea - skunkworks
	labs are collaborative efforts.
</p>

<p>
	Lab's also have supporters, which are not explicitly members of the team. This is used to represent people who have an interest in seeing
	the lab completed or otherwise support the lab's goals. Labs with a large number of supporters should reflect the importance or
	necessity of the lab.
</p>

<p class="lead">
	Lab Updates
</p>

<p>
	Overall progress in the lab is tracked through lab updates which take one of two forms: a status update or a comment. Only team members
	can provide status updates and when they do so they provide a percentage of completeness. This percentage is how much of <em>their</em> work is
	complete, not the overall lab. The average of all most recent status updates for each user is the overall progress of the lab.
</p>

<p>
	On the other hand any user, not just team members, can comment on labs. This allows people who aren't actively involved to still be able to
	play a part or contribute to the lab. Comments are a great way of providing feedback in a transparent manner.
</p>

